Jul 20, 2021, 10:36 PM
no longer human by osamu dazai is a semi-autobiographical novel about the authors life. dazai is known for first person autobiographical fiction (aka this shit reads like a spam post, they’re aren’t chapters but notebooks). many of the elements that happen to the main character yozo were taken from dazai’s life, and shortly after the writing of this book he committed suicide, leading many to believe that this book is his will. dazai (which is just a pen name) spent most of his life depressed or struggling with addiction, having attempted suicide four times with the last one being successful (mf has more privilege then me 😔), which is reflected in yozo. ever since yozo was born, he’s felt disqualified to be human, despising the two facedness of humanity and was sexually assaulted by his servants. these traumas would lead him to indulge himself with smoking, alcohol and prostitutes, and would continuously lament about his hatred of humanity and its nature. he plays himself as a clown in order to never reveal his true self to anyone, essentially ostracizing himself to save the pain of a relationship. yozo represents nihilism but most of all the pain of existentialism. though yozo often makes disgusting and morally wrong actions, the book concludes from an outside point of view that he was a good child. it depicts depression and the cynical cycle of hatred in the most real light, and it comes off as authentic and not as edgy or rebellious. yozo feels indescribably alienated but finds comfort in that alienation, as many rather be comfortable then be better. aight i’m done with this formal ass voice this book da shit ong. like he basically describes so many existential thoughts and questions what it means to live. he depicts mental illness as what it really is, because mental illness causes people to do a lot of shitty things (does that mean they shouldn’t be held responsible? probably not). he also depicts how easy it is not to connect with people and to be unauthentic but that causes you to run away from life itself and causes destruction. shits just insane bro just read it. it’s literally a well written version of my spam post while i’m depressed

Jul 4, 2021, 8:30 PM
Just finished reading the metamorphosis. crazy how kafka is able to pack so many ideas in such a short story. so ig spoiler ahead. one theme is that the idea of something is scarier then the appearance. the whole family is horrified and disgusted by how gregor looks but when he dies they’re completely fine with looking at him. which signifies that what really horrified his family was the idea that he became such a creature rather then his appearance which we are first led to believe. another theme is the arbitrariness and abursidity that money holds in our society. when gregor first wakes up from his metamorphosis the only thing that really stresses on his mind is his job and work, and not the fact that he’s an insect. this at first seems absurd to the reader but slowly after seeing how the family has had to suffer from the lost of his income, it really becomes apparent how important money is and why that stress meant so much. along with this life is just absurd, things just happen without any intention and many of the characters are not extremely surprised by his appearance. sympathy has its boundaries, even tho it’s a shit thing to say he is actually a burden to a family. it causes him to be depressed and to jill himself but at the end of the day people have to prioritize there own lives. also the notion that physical form dictates mental form is also a theme. because he is physically an insect he slowly becomes more and more like an insect mentally, even in his attempts to reject that metamorphosis. i think the biggest theme out of this whole book is regardless of appearance to treat everyone the same. like i remember my ela 10 teacher told us that when he asked homeless people what the worst part is that when people ignore them because it dehumanizes them i’m like damn ima not do that. and tbh homeless people are pretty nice they just look scary and shit. and i think it’s the same here. if his family just got over his appearance (which they can clearly do which is apparent at the end) this wouldn’t have been a tragedy. but because of his form and the increased burden they put on them, they dehumanizes him and look at him with disgust. however when he dies

just finished another book. read this in 3 days and annotated the shit out of it. so that’s why it took me so long. but holy fuck this book is good. idk if it’s because i annotated so much but it’s so so good. the writing is harrowing and gripping. literally made me feel this big ball of tension and unease in my heart. love it. the antagonist is literally the goat antagonist. his philosophy and character is so so so well made. it’s interesting but disgusting and depraved at the same time. like he rarely made king speeches but when he did i literally highlighted the entire page. my favourite quote, and it’s simple but when you read what it’s around it it’s insane, is “god is war.” also this book isn’t for the faint of heart, the imagery is graphic and the entire book is about depravity and violence. and it’s very graphic. it explores the nature of violence and depravity and what makes people motivated to do it. but ultimately the quote from a review in the front of the novel said it best, “a classic american novel of regeneration through violence.” spoilers ahead. the whole character arc of the kid, who is never named, is that at the start he is a bloodlustful violent individual with no humanity in sight. we are taken on an adventure of extreme violence where they kill aboriginals and scalp them for money. the novel increasingly gets more depraved and contrasting the antogonist, the judge, the kid becomes more human and his morality is revealed. the judge thinks of the kid as his ideal son (because of his beliefs) and tries to enforce his values onto him. but the kid rejects his beliefs. eventually the judge realizes his ideal son will never be like him and kills him in such a gruesome way that novel refuses to describe it even tho we’ve seen some really shitty things. the judge kills the kid in order to push away the fact that he is alone in his journey. nobody will join the judge with his depravity. ultimately he may be the last one standing but he is alone in the world. his acts of depravity isolate him. also the novel concludes that ultimately evil will outdo good but evil is lonely which anybody can do

Jun 17, 2021, 10:05 PM
so i just listened to 11.5 hours of crime and punishment today so it’s time for a review time. first of all i’m kind of disappointed but that is because i thought very highly of the book. i thought it would be easily a 10 and contend with eva but that didn’t happen. really the title is basically the story, the protagonist does a crime and his punishment is outlined. it explores the flaws in western philosophy such as existentialism, utilitarianism, nihilism and ubermensch (even before neisctzhe) and basically concludes that the philosophical beliefs of russian christianity were better (which was quite a conflict during dostoyevsky time of writing). i think the best explored theme is that crimes or immoral actions will weigh on the human conscience and causes the criminal to be unable to receive or give love properly. one must repent or take responsibility for there actions. but along with that one must receive unconditional love (even if they are unable to accept it) in order to change or be better. it also explores how shit poverty is and how horrible it is. some aspects it was explored well and others it’s meh. i think the main problem i have which won’t let me rate it higher is that the themes are just not explored as well as i thought and the book does not represent much; it only represents one idea and not multiple ideas or even the entirety of life. i don’t feel the complexity of the issue has been explored lots. that being said the ability of dostoyevsky to deconstruct atheistic philosophy is admirable and is one of the first to shit on existentialism and utilitarianism in literature. but what i find most impressive about dostoyevsky writing is his writing. i found myself very entertained throughout the novel and very emotional at the end. he builds up the characters very well and i think this is one of the best novels (in terms of appeal) i’ve ever read. there’s a reason i was able to sit for almost 12 hours reading this book. it’s fucking entertaining even with its somewhat mundane plot. and i felt my heart aching at the final couple of chapters. this book truly is able to make the reader very emotional and make one feel as guilty as the protagonist.

process everything. but i think this book definitely deserves another reading. i think at a technical standpoint there’s a lot. tons of subtle symbols and motifs. and at the surface it’s just shit talking bureaucracy and totalitarianism but i think it speaks a lot to our society too and also the human condition. ultimately, justice is done for victory and not for justice, we can see this in cancel culture and how profitable the justice system is. and i think the most important point kafka brings up is that the reality is we’re all just dogs in this world that are controlled by other dogs. and ultimately society wears us all down to accept our fate. i really enjoy how dark kafkas writing is, how depressing and gritty it is. it describes the bureaucracy well and in a really shitty light. really it shows the grittiness of life, our fate is really not up to us and we get work down by that fate until we give in and die. the people that are used to their fate don’t realize how muffled the air they breathe is. i need to definitely reread one of the chapters cause it’s so so confusing and idk what it means. whether or not we want to we can’t escape the system and it constantly controls our life. and at the end of the day society wears its citizens down of all its humanistic features to benefit itself. and it displays the question on is life worth living really i just binge read 15 volumes of this manga called homunculus. so manga review!!! k but trigger warning if you’re gonna read the manga, they’re displays of rape and drilling a hole into your head and also suicide. but anyways back to the review. i feel this review will be half assed cause i need more time to think about it. but it’s very experimental in terms of how it plays with perspective, genuinely a very confusing manga to read because it comes from basically a deluded person (or possibly not) and his perspective on issues. so horrific crimes he has done seem okay because of the experimental perspective and is genuinely very confusing. i feel like this manga can be easily interpreted the wrong way (he rapes someone for her “own good”, and often completely destroys people to reconstruct them) but i think if we consider the manga as a whole, it is really a commentary about how easy it is to make people feel empathetic for shitty people and because he reaches his own demise in the end, it shows how deluded this guy really was. the commentary is insane, there’s commentary about society and ultimately what it means to be human and questions everything about being human to its core. it questions whether it’s ethical to completely destroy someone to reconstruct them and shows how much influence you should put in order to help them change. and honestly i can relate to certain aspects of the character a lot and it’s gotten me to question whether or not i’m on the same destructive path. by showing humans and their depravity as well as their flaws in clear view, it really questions on what being human is. ultimately, the people in the bottom of society and the top 1% are much of the same. the ability the empathize with every character is something that is truly a skill done by the author and questions how our society is constructed as well as question the validity of ourselves. this book is pretty insane this is atleast a 9.5 i gotta think about more to be a 10. i’m way too tired to be using my brain rhis@much i might make another one tomorrow because i’m not doing this manga justice.

okay book review first. brave new world. at first i was reading this book and i was like bruh another dystopia. i hate dystopias because they state facts instead of exploring the reason behind them. ngl john killing himself actually saved the entire book. because john lives in the other extreme of civilization, while civilization only cares for happiness, john only cares for truth and completely ignores his humanity. they are the same robot in two different ways. by showing this stark contrast the book ultimately concludes that we need truth and happiness to live and by living in one extreme we lose our humanity, which is a really basic point but the way it’s executed is done really well. i think the main reason it’s done so well is that we are led to believe that john way of living is so much better, but realize that it’s worse or even much worse then the civilizations way of living. by exploring how easy it is to fall into the trap, ultimately the author shows how easy it is to live in a dystopia. ultimately the last chapters allow this book to serve as a critique on character rather then a critique on society. what a i disliked about the book (and dystopia in general) is that they create this world that’s a dystopia and it’s obvious why it could be reached and why it’s so shit. simply pointing out these facts is a really boring and unimpactful way of exploring being human. but by exploring the descent and the personal emotions that lead to flawed mindsets speaks more volume and is much more relatable. by exploring the fragility of humanity through a single character rather then a society shows the complexity of being human and the want to live in an ideal world. ultimately the end saves this book by its ass. 7/10. first day of school was alright. was really tired and was lowkey grinding for school but yeah. happy i saw my physics teacher. returned home and grinded terraria. my mood is swinging to being happy again, being unstable is shit asf. really want to talk to my therapist and can’t wait till thursday. just got shit to proccess through. my therapist carries my life. i need to consume more media, critiquing shit is so fun

Jul 31, 2020, 8:36 PM
dog shit album review. Blonde is an album that explores Frank’s past relationships and immaturity. Often, the songs are Frank reflecting upon his own life and relationships, reflecting upon his mistakes and immaturities. This allows the listener to relate, as often many of those reflections are common, especially after a romantic relationship. Basically this put me into my feels. A major theme to Blonde is duality. The entire album is filled with this idea of duality, including the title name. The official title name is Blonde but on the album cover the title name is Blond. Though they mean the same thing, blond in French is the masculine form whilst blonde is the feminine form. This minor detail relates to the album as Frank struggles with the duality of his masculinity and femininity. Another example of duality is through the guitar riff in the ninth track “Nights.” This guitar riff occurs exactly 30 minutes in the 60 minute album, splitting Blonde ​into two parts. By splitting the album into two parts we are able to see a change in his attitudes towards his past. In the first eight songs, Frank is reminiscing and trying to relive the memories he had towards his past lovers, even trying to win them back. The songs in the second part shows Frank accepting the past and wishing the best for his past lovers. I could go on for days about this theme but I’m just going to end it here because honestly bro this too long fam. The production on ​Blonde​ ​is honestly one of my favourite things on the album. If I’m going to be honest I never listened to the lyrics closely most of the time but rather just for the musical appeal of the album as a whole. The production is a perfect balance of experimentation and appeal, not too strange but not too common. Along with this, the vocals combine perfectly with the production and allows the listener to feel immersed in the world Frank creates. Even though the production is immaculate, for me personally it took me a couple of listens to get used to the sound. For me personally, the songs with the best production are “Pink + White,” “Self Control,” and “Nights.” I could go on and on about this album, dissecting every lyric
